================================================================
        REST API METHODS — FUNDAMENTAL STRUCTURE
        How Every Method Is Built · What Goes Where · Why
================================================================


----------------------------------------------------------------
THE FUNDAMENTAL PATTERN — SAME FOR ALL 5 METHODS
----------------------------------------------------------------

Every single method you write in the Controller follows
this exact same skeleton:

    @HttpMethodAnnotation("url-path")        ← Line 1: what request to listen for
    public ReturnType methodName(inputs) {   ← Line 2: method signature
        // Line 3: do something with DB
        // Line 4: return something back
    }

That is it. Every method is just these 4 things.
The only thing that CHANGES between methods is:
    - Which annotation (@Get, @Post, @Put, @Delete)
    - What return type (List, User, String)
    - What inputs (nothing, @PathVariable, @RequestBody, or both)
    - Which JPA method inside (findAll, findById, save, deleteById)


----------------------------------------------------------------
THE 4 BUILDING BLOCKS OF EVERY METHOD
----------------------------------------------------------------

BLOCK 1 — ANNOTATION (what HTTP request to catch)
    Written  → above the method, starts with @
    Purpose  → tells Spring which HTTP request triggers this method
    Options  → @GetMapping / @PostMapping / @PutMapping / @DeleteMapping
    Can have → a URL path inside like ("/{id}") or nothing

BLOCK 2 — METHOD SIGNATURE (what the method is and takes)
    Written  → public ReturnType methodName(parameters)
    Parts    →
        public        = anyone can call it (must be public for Spring)
        ReturnType    = what this method gives back (List, User, String)
        methodName    = any name you choose (doesn't matter to Spring)
        parameters    = what inputs it needs (@PathVariable, @RequestBody)

BLOCK 3 — METHOD BODY (what actually happens inside)
    Written  → inside { } curly braces
    Purpose  → talk to database using the repository object
    Always   → userRepository.someJpaMethod()

BLOCK 4 — RETURN STATEMENT (what gets sent back as response)
    Written  → return something;
    Purpose  → this value gets converted to JSON and sent back
    Exception → deleteById has no return value from JPA
                so you manually return a String message


----------------------------------------------------------------
GET ALL USERS — FUNDAMENTAL BREAKDOWN
----------------------------------------------------------------

    @GetMapping                              ← BLOCK 1: catch GET /users
    public List<User> getAllUsers() {        ← BLOCK 2: signature
        return userRepository.findAll();     ← BLOCK 3+4: body + return
    }

    ANNOTATION:
        @GetMapping
        → no path inside = listens to base URL /users
        → GET = fetching/reading data, not changing anything

    METHOD SIGNATURE:
        public          → accessible to Spring and outside world
        List<User>      → return type = many users in a collection
        getAllUsers      → method name (you chose this)
        ()              → empty = needs NO input from the request

    METHOD BODY:
        userRepository.findAll()
        → goes to DB
        → runs SELECT * FROM user table
        → gets back all rows as a List of User objects

    RETURN:
        return userRepository.findAll();
        → that List gets converted to JSON array automatically
        → sent back as HTTP response


----------------------------------------------------------------
GET USER BY ID — FUNDAMENTAL BREAKDOWN
----------------------------------------------------------------

    @GetMapping("/{id}")                                      ← BLOCK 1
    public User getUserById(@PathVariable Long id) {          ← BLOCK 2
        return userRepository.findById(id).orElse(null);     ← BLOCK 3+4
    }

    ANNOTATION:
        @GetMapping("/{id}")
        → "/{id}" is a URL slot — changes per request
        → /users/1 or /users/5 or /users/99
        → { } means this part is a variable, not fixed text

    METHOD SIGNATURE:
        public          → accessible
        User            → return type = ONE single User (not a list)
        getUserById     → method name
        (@PathVariable Long id)
            @PathVariable → grab the number from URL slot
            Long          → data type of that number
            id            → variable name to hold that number

    METHOD BODY:
        userRepository.findById(id)
        → runs SELECT * FROM user WHERE id = ?
        → returns Optional<User> (may or may not exist)

        .orElse(null)
        → if found    → return the User object
        → if not found → return null instead of crashing

    RETURN:
        return userRepository.findById(id).orElse(null);
        → found User gets converted to JSON object
        → not found returns null (empty response)


----------------------------------------------------------------
POST CREATE USER — FUNDAMENTAL BREAKDOWN
----------------------------------------------------------------

    @PostMapping                                   ← BLOCK 1
    public User createUser(@RequestBody User user) {  ← BLOCK 2
        return userRepository.save(user);          ← BLOCK 3+4
    }

    ANNOTATION:
        @PostMapping
        → no path = listens to base URL /users
        → POST = sending data TO server, creating something new
        → no /{id} because we are creating, no existing ID yet

    METHOD SIGNATURE:
        public          → accessible
        User            → return type = the newly created User
        createUser      → method name
        (@RequestBody User user)
            @RequestBody  → grab JSON from request body
                            convert it to a User Java object
            User          → type of that object
            user          → variable name to hold it

    METHOD BODY:
        userRepository.save(user)
        → user object has no ID (not set yet)
        → JPA sees no ID → runs INSERT INTO user table
        → DB auto-generates the ID
        → returns the saved User now WITH the generated ID

    RETURN:
        return userRepository.save(user);
        → saved User (with ID) gets converted to JSON
        → sent back so caller knows what ID was assigned


----------------------------------------------------------------
PUT UPDATE USER — FUNDAMENTAL BREAKDOWN
----------------------------------------------------------------

    @PutMapping("/{id}")                                            ← BLOCK 1
    public User updateUser(@PathVariable Long id,                   ← BLOCK 2
                           @RequestBody User user) {
        User existing = userRepository.findById(id).orElse(null);  ← BLOCK 3
        if (existing != null) {
            existing.setName(user.getName());
            existing.setEmail(user.getEmail());
            return userRepository.save(existing);                   ← BLOCK 4
        }
        return null;
    }

    ANNOTATION:
        @PutMapping("/{id}")
        → PUT = updating existing data
        → needs /{id} to know WHICH record to update

    METHOD SIGNATURE:
        public          → accessible
        User            → return type = the updated User
        updateUser      → method name
        TWO parameters this time:
            @PathVariable Long id     → which user (from URL)
            @RequestBody User user    → new data to update with (from body)

    METHOD BODY — more steps than others:
        Step 1: User existing = userRepository.findById(id).orElse(null);
                → first fetch the OLD record from DB
                → can't update something you haven't found first

        Step 2: if (existing != null)
                → check if that user actually exists
                → != means "not equal to"
                → if found → go inside if block
                → if not found → skip to return null

        Step 3: existing.setName(user.getName());
                existing.setEmail(user.getEmail());
                → user.getName()      = get new value from body JSON
                → existing.setName()  = put new value into old object
                → do this for every field you want to update

        Step 4: return userRepository.save(existing);
                → existing object HAS an ID
                → JPA sees existing ID → runs UPDATE SQL (not INSERT)
                → same save() method, different behavior based on ID

    RETURN:
        return userRepository.save(existing);  → updated User
        return null;                           → if user not found


----------------------------------------------------------------
DELETE USER — FUNDAMENTAL BREAKDOWN
----------------------------------------------------------------

    @DeleteMapping("/{id}")                     ← BLOCK 1
    public String deleteUser(@PathVariable Long id) {   ← BLOCK 2
        userRepository.deleteById(id);          ← BLOCK 3
        return "User " + id + " deleted!";      ← BLOCK 4
    }

    ANNOTATION:
        @DeleteMapping("/{id}")
        → DELETE = removing data
        → needs /{id} to know WHICH record to remove

    METHOD SIGNATURE:
        public          → accessible
        String          → return type = plain text message
                          (nothing meaningful to return after delete
                           so just send a confirmation text)
        deleteUser      → method name
        (@PathVariable Long id)
            → grab the ID number from URL path

    METHOD BODY:
        userRepository.deleteById(id);
        → runs DELETE FROM user WHERE id = ?
        → returns NOTHING (void) — just silently deletes
        → no object comes back unlike save() or findAll()

    RETURN:
        return "User " + id + " deleted!";
        → manually build a String message
        → + joins text pieces together
        → if id=1 result is "User 1 deleted!"
        → this String is sent back as plain text response


